🌈 Prism RL Environment: Demo Walkthrough
Follow these steps to demonstrate the full capabilities of Prism to the hackathon judges.

1. Preparation
Ensure your Space is live (e.g., https://huggingface.co/spaces/YOUR_USER/prism).
Verify that the BACKEND CONNECTED badge is green.
If you haven't yet, set up an API key for Groq or Gemini in the dashboard to show real LLM behavior.
2. Part A: The Live Dashboard (Visual Demo)
Step 1: Environment Selection
Open the dashboard in your browser.
Select Software Debugging or Market Research from the domain list.
Click RESET ENVIRONMENT to start a fresh episode.
Point out the Task Execution Graph—all nodes are currently PENDING.
Step 2: Agent Autonomy (Active Model)
Use the Model Selector at the top.
Choose Groq/llama-3.3-70b-versatile or Gemini-2.0-flash.
Click SET ACTIVE.
Toggle AUTO: ON in the Active Environment panel.
Observation:
Watch the Step Performance Log. Mention that it records the latency of each LLM call.
Watch the Reward Trajectories chart. Explain the 5 components (Progress, Atomic, Coord, Hallucination, Terminal).
Point to the Task Graph—watch nodes flip to DONE as the agent executes tools.
Step 3: Handling Failures (Optional but Impressive)
If an INJECTED FAILURE ACTIVE banner appears, explain that the environment just corrupted a tool call.
Show how the agent uses checkpoint and rollback (in the logs) to recover.
3. Part B: The Multi-Model Tournament
Step 1: Racing Models
Scroll down to the Model Agnosticism Proof section.
Ensure you have at least 2 models configured (e.g., Llama and Gemini).
Click START TOURNAMENT.
Observation:
Watch the Model Status Badges (e.g., llama-3.3: running).
Show how the chart draws two lines simultaneously.
Explain: "This proves our environment is model-agnostic. We are evaluating two different LLMs on the exact same task in real-time."
4. Part C: The Terminal (Programmatic Demo)
Step 1: Rich Demo Script
Judges love seeing raw API interactions. Run this from your local machine (pointing to your HF URL):

bash
python run_demo.py https://YOUR_USER-prism.hf.space
Explain: "This script exercises the Gymnasium-style API over HTTP, showing that the environment is fully compliant with OpenEnv standards."

Step 2: The Grader Proof
Go to the Tournament Archive at the bottom of the dashboard.
Click View JSON on a finished record.
Show the final_reward and grader_score.
Explain: "Every episode is automatically graded by a domain-specific rubric (e.g., pytest for code, rubric for research), removing human bias from the evaluation loop."
5. Summary Pitch for Judges
"Prism doesn't just evaluate if an agent finishes a task. It evaluates how it finishes. We use three adversarial injectors to stress-test coordination, atomicity, and domain transfer, turning reliability from a weakness into a trainable RL signal."